You are working in a strict, scalable Vue 3 application.

TECH STACK

- Vue 3 (latest stable)
- Vite
- TypeScript (strict mode, noImplicitAny true)
- Pinia
- Vue Router
- Tailwind CSS (latest stable)

────────────────────────
CORE PRINCIPLES
────────────────────────

- Use Composition API only.
- <script setup lang="ts" name="ComponentName"> is mandatory.
- No Options API.
- No default exports.
- One component per file.
- Strong separation of concerns.
- Components must remain presentational whenever possible.
- Business logic must never live inside components.
- Architecture must support scalability and modularity.
- No circular dependencies between layers.

────────────────────────
NAMING CONVENTIONS
────────────────────────

- Components → kebab-case folder, index.vue component name.
- Composables → useSomething.ts in domain folder.
- Stores → <domain>.store.ts
- Services → <entity>.service.ts
- Types → index.ts inside domain folder.
- Utils → camelCase function names.
- No abbreviations in naming.

────────────────────────
TYPES SYSTEM
────────────────────────

- Strict typing only. Never use:
    any
    unknown (unless truly unavoidable)
    implicit returns
- Prefer interfaces for objects.
- Types must contain zero logic.

Folder structure:

/types
    /api
    /app
    /ui
    /utils

Structure:

types/<domain>/<entity>/index.ts

Rules:

- Separate API request and response types.
- Never mix API and domain/app types.
- Create mapping functions if transformation is required.
- All service responses must return typed data.
- No type duplication across domains.

────────────────────────
COMPONENT RULES
────────────────────────

Location:
components/<domain>/<component-name>/index.vue

Example:
components/ui/button/index.vue
components/app/challenge/index.vue

Inside component order:

1. Imports
2. Dont use Props interface
3. defineProps
4. defineEmits
5. Store usage
6. Composables usage
7. Local state
8. Computed
9. Methods
10. Lifecycle hooks
11. Use lazy loading for imports.
12. Always use the comments for sections to keep the code clean and maintainable. Use it when needed. Example:
    <script setup lang="ts" name="ComponentName">
    // Imports
    // Types
    // Props
    // Emits
    // Store
    // Composables
    // State
    // Computed
    // Methods
    // Lifecycle hooks
    </script>

Rules:

- No inline functions in template.
- No async logic in template.
- No direct API calls.
- No business logic.
- No data transformation logic.
- Do not directly mutate store state in template.
- Use Tailwind utilities only.
- Always use scoped CSS.
- No deep selectors.
- Do not use !important.
- If using v-if for example <p v-if="codition"> please use <template v-if="codition"> <p> </p> </template> instead.


────────────────────────
PROPS TYPING RULES
────────────────────────

- Props must ALWAYS be defined using inline generic typing.
- Never create a separate Props interface.
- Never use runtime props declaration.
- Never use defineProps({ ... }) object syntax.
- Always use this exact pattern:

defineProps<{
  propName?: Type;
}>();

- Do not assign defineProps to a variable.
- Do not use withDefaults unless explicitly required.
- Props generic type must be written inline inside defineProps.


────────────────────────
EMITS STANDARD (STRICT)
────────────────────────

- All component events must follow the "onAction" naming convention.
- Event names must start with "on" followed by PascalCase action.

Correct examples:
  onNext
  onSubmit
  onClose
  onSave
  onCancel
  onUpdate

Incorrect examples:
  next
  submit
  close
  save
  update:modelValue
  kebab-case events

- Events must always be defined using typed inline generic syntax.
- defineEmits must always be assigned to a const named "emit".
- Never use string array syntax for emits.
- Never use untyped emits.

Required pattern:

const emit = defineEmits<{
  (e: 'onAction'): void;
}>();

- If payload exists, it must be strictly typed.
- Never use any in emit payload.

────────────────────────
COMPOSABLES RULES
────────────────────────

Location:
composables/<domain>/useSomething.ts

Responsibilities:

- Feature-level business logic.
- Local feature state.
- Orchestration between store and service.
- Mapping API → domain types.

Rules:

- Must not mutate Pinia store state directly (only via store actions).
- Must not contain rendering logic.
- Async operations must use try/catch.
- Errors must be returned or forwarded.
- Keep return object minimal.
- Do not expose internal implementation details.

────────────────────────
PINIA STORES
────────────────────────

Location:
stores/<domain>/<domain>.store.ts

Stores are responsible for:

- Global state
- Session state
- Auth state
- Feature flags
- Cross-module domain state

Rules:

- No UI logic.
- No template logic.
- API calls must be performed inside actions.
- State must be fully typed.
- Actions must be async if calling services.
- Avoid god-store pattern (split by domain).
- Never access localStorage directly outside store layer.

────────────────────────
SERVICES LAYER
────────────────────────

Location:
services/<domain>/<entity>.service.ts

Responsibilities:

- API communication only.
- Use centralized api client.
- Return strictly typed data.
- Map raw response if necessary.

Rules:

- No global state mutation.
- No UI logic.
- No side effects outside request/response handling.
- No direct usage inside components.
- No business logic.

────────────────────────
UTILS
────────────────────────

- Pure functions only.
- No state.
- No side effects.
- No DOM access.
- Fully typed.
- Generic utilities belong in /utils.
- Domain utilities belong inside module folder.

────────────────────────
ROUTER
────────────────────────

- All routes typed.
- Route meta must contain:
    requiresAuth: boolean
    permissions?: string[]

- Auth/permission checks must be abstracted.
- Navigation guards must remain thin.
- No business logic in router config.

────────────────────────
ENVIRONMENT & CONFIG
────────────────────────

- Never use import.meta.env inside components.
- Create:

services/config/app.config.ts

- Environment must be mapped to typed config object.
- Components and composables must consume config, not env directly.

────────────────────────
TAILWIND & STYLING
────────────────────────

- Tailwind utility classes only.
- No inline style attributes.
- No global CSS overrides.
- Layout patterns must be abstracted to reusable layout components.
- UI primitives must live in components/ui.
- No global styles.
- BEM naming convention for classes.

────────────────────────
ERROR HANDLING
────────────────────────

- All async functions must use try/catch.
- No silent catch blocks.
- No console.log in production code.
- Errors must be either:
    handled,
    propagated,
    or forwarded to centralized handler.

────────────────────────
ANTI-PATTERNS (STRICTLY FORBIDDEN)
────────────────────────

- API calls inside components.
- Business logic in template.
- Store logic inside services.
- Direct DOM manipulation.
- Direct env usage outside config layer.
- Mixing API and domain types.
- Returning raw axios response to UI.
- Using any type.
- Massive multi-responsibility components.

────────────────────────
WHEN GENERATING NEW CODE
────────────────────────

- Strictly follow existing folder conventions.
- Do not invent new patterns.
- Respect layering.
- Maintain strong type safety.
- Prefer small focused modules.
- Produce production-ready scalable code.


────────────────────────
BOOLEAN STATE NAMING RULE (STRICT)
────────────────────────

- All boolean variables must start with "is".
- The pattern must always be:

is + PascalCaseStateName

Correct examples:
  isLoading
  isActive
  isOpen
  isVisible
  isProgress
  isDisabled
  isAuthenticated
  isSubmitting

Incorrect examples:
  loading
  active
  open
  visible
  progress
  hasError
  disabled
  authenticated

- Do not use prefixes like:
  has
  can
  should
  enable
  disable

- Boolean refs, store state, computed values, and props must all follow the "isXxx" pattern.
- The "is" prefix is mandatory regardless of context (component, store, composable, or local state).